feat: vite replace webpack (#1966)

| Q            | A
|--------------| ---
| Bug fix?     | no
| New feature? | yes
| BC-Break?    | yes
| License      | MIT

This PR replaces webpack with vite. Vite is much faster in dev mode, comparing to webpack build + watch. Thanks to hmr and es6 imports. To integrate vite, we need to make a lot of changes to fix the build.

* Integrate dependency injection plugin
* Replace the icon font plugin (no powerted by fantasticon)
* Fixing import statements
* Add url rewriting workaround
* Replace urijs with native URL
* Add twig functions and symfony configuration to load various builds
* Change `assets/enhavo` to `assets/admin`
* Use es6 modules for all enhavo packages

This PR let the master be unstable because not all work is done. We still having some issues with select2 and tinymce intergration. But soon we will be replaceing the forms api with our vue forms, so we will fix this in a later PR.

Also the js tests will fail, because we will rewrite them with `vitest` to stack to one ecosystem.

- Checks whether the new "author_id" column does NOT exist, rather than checking whether the original "author" column exists.
- Does not have any verifiable impact in the field, but may prevent crashing the repository on startup if the following conditions apply:

  3. Updated source again to post-migration and ran the repository (in that case, the "author" column would be there, but so would the "author_id" and the liquibase script would fail on startup)

2529

# Enforces username + authentication provider tuple as requirement to resolve users all across the codebase

- Injects the IOAuthProviderRegistry in a number of services/controllers where user-related operations were previously resolving users by username only, in order to infer the correct authentication provider ID for the currently logged in user
- User-resolving service and cache functionalities (e.g. in account service) have their APIs change accordingly (e.g. requiring an Authentication object or a UserDto instead of a username to resolve a user, etc.)
- Some boilerplate cleanup of current Authentication resolution through SecurityContextHolder where already resolved downstream in referenced services
- Enforces UserDto as main vector for user resolution parametrization across the code base (as the DTO already features both username and authentication provider ID)
- Refactors comment authorship (was expressed by username, now by user ID FK) impacting on front-end, controller, service, anonymization listener and of course entities / repository
- Extraneous: further optimization of user caches to reduce repository round trips
- Extraneous/cosmetic: further replacement of "tenant" variable names with "workspace" to homologate and clarify the value in question represents a JCR workspace ID
- Cosmetic: renames some additional variables according to the object type (e.g. "user" -> "authentication/auth" etc.
- Reworks user resolution in ModelRepositoryFactory implementation / general deprecation of IUserContext-only APIs also in various Policy classes (part of which will require manual testing due to insufficient coverage)
- Adds resolution pathways to RepositoryInitializer when making sysadmins based on yml configuration - either _one_ or no user is resolved by username - ambiguities fail early and log
- IOAuthProviderRegistry provides an "anonymous", mock IOauthProvider when no IOauthProvider can handle the current Authentication object (i.e. the user is anonymous)
- Find methods in UserRegistry refactored to reflect user resolution requirements
- ISearchService API refactored to favor Authentication over IUserContext
- UserDto enriched with some boilerplate utility methods
- Controllers where users were formerly resolved by a username path variable now take a UserDto as the request body or part thereof if a request body is already required --> similarly, some front-end is refactored to send the required payload
- CommentDTO de-couples from entity it was inheriting from
- Refactors all test classes and general test utility classes broken by the API changes save for UI and benchmark tests
- OAuth provider configurations now expose their provider's ID as well, which is necessary for the DB authorities extractor

Signed-off-by: Menahem Julien Raccah Lisei <menahemjulien.raccahlisei@bosch-si.com>

Bulk of the feature:

1. The request access to namespace form now accepts 3 parameters in its standalone version:
   - userId (the username of the technical user proxy that is the target of the request)
   - oauthProvider (optional if userId is provided: the oauthprovided the technical user should authenticate with)
   - clientName (optional and cosmetic if userId is provided: will simply display on the form for ease of use but will not be persisted or sent anywhere)
   When parametrized, the form will display a representation of the technical user, either retrieved from the Vorto repository if existing, or to be created after acknowledging some legalese (a dynamic button is featured for that).
   The form now features both technical user resolution by given userId, and creation if applicable.
   Some additional error handling and legalese apply as well.

* Integrate dependency injection plugin
* Replace the icon font plugin (no powerted by fantasticon)
* Fixing import statements
* Add url rewriting workaround
* Replace urijs with native URL
* Add twig functions and symfony configuration to load various builds
* Change `assets/enhavo` to `assets/admin`
* Use es6 modules for all enhavo packages

This PR let the master be unstable because not all work is done. We still having some issues with select2 and tinymce intergration. But soon we will be replaceing the forms api with our vue forms, so we will fix this in a later PR.

Also the js tests will fail, because we will rewrite them with `vitest` to stack to one ecosystem.

# Enforces username + authentication provider tuple as requirement to resolve users all across the codebase

- Injects the IOAuthProviderRegistry in a number of services/controllers where user-related operations were previously resolving users by username only, in order to infer the correct authentication provider ID for the currently logged in user
- User-resolving service and cache functionalities (e.g. in account service) have their APIs change accordingly (e.g. requiring an Authentication object or a UserDto instead of a username to resolve a user, etc.)
- Some boilerplate cleanup of current Authentication resolution through SecurityContextHolder where already resolved downstream in referenced services
- Enforces UserDto as main vector for user resolution parametrization across the code base (as the DTO already features both username and authentication provider ID)
- Refactors comment authorship (was expressed by username, now by user ID FK) impacting on front-end, controller, service, anonymization listener and of course entities / repository
- Extraneous: further optimization of user caches to reduce repository round trips
- Extraneous/cosmetic: further replacement of "tenant" variable names with "workspace" to homologate and clarify the value in question represents a JCR workspace ID
- Cosmetic: renames some additional variables according to the object type (e.g. "user" -> "authentication/auth" etc.
- Reworks user resolution in ModelRepositoryFactory implementation / general deprecation of IUserContext-only APIs also in various Policy classes (part of which will require manual testing due to insufficient coverage)
- Adds resolution pathways to RepositoryInitializer when making sysadmins based on yml configuration - either _one_ or no user is resolved by username - ambiguities fail early and log
- IOAuthProviderRegistry provides an "anonymous", mock IOauthProvider when no IOauthProvider can handle the current Authentication object (i.e. the user is anonymous)
- Find methods in UserRegistry refactored to reflect user resolution requirements
- ISearchService API refactored to favor Authentication over IUserContext
- UserDto enriched with some boilerplate utility methods
- Controllers where users were formerly resolved by a username path variable now take a UserDto as the request body or part thereof if a request body is already required --> similarly, some front-end is refactored to send the required payload
- CommentDTO de-couples from entity it was inheriting from
- Refactors all test classes and general test utility classes broken by the API changes save for UI and benchmark tests
- OAuth provider configurations now expose their provider's ID as well, which is necessary for the DB authorities extractor

2462_followup

Bulk of the feature:

1. The request access to namespace form now accepts 3 parameters in its standalone version:
   - userId (the username of the technical user proxy that is the target of the request)
   - oauthProvider (optional if userId is provided: the oauthprovided the technical user should authenticate with)
   - clientName (optional and cosmetic if userId is provided: will simply display on the form for ease of use but will not be persisted or sent anywhere)
   When parametrized, the form will display a representation of the technical user, either retrieved from the Vorto repository if existing, or to be created after acknowledging some legalese (a dynamic button is featured for that).
   The form now features both technical user resolution by given userId, and creation if applicable.
   Some additional error handling and legalese apply as well.

2. The standalone and modal versions of the form can still work with no parameters as they did before, with no change.

3. Some far-related improvements in the DTOs and references
4. Additional controller endpoint required
5. Slight improvement in the e-mail beint sent when successful, for readability (still looks ugly though, with no styling)
